result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Jury trial - 12 person on September 25, 2014 at 08:30 am.

9:37 Attorney Sean W O'Neill in court.  Elizabeth R Constable appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty O'Neill asks that the trial be continued as he has another trial set for that date.  Atty Constable does not object to moving the trial date but would like to start trying as soon as possible.  Atty Constable asks if witness would need to be at all trials.  O'Neill indicates that the witness would be needed at all in reference to victim - Clausen.  Atty Constable indicates that victim is not part of 14CF42.  Atty O'Neill extends out his request for speedy trial.  Atty Constable objects to extending all three case out to September.  Court is inclined to extended out to September.  Court advises counsel to contact his judicial assistant to set a date in September for trial.

Court addresses Bond Pledge in case that was dismissed on Fosnot and informs O'Neill that the court will not be returning the bond as it is not the policy of the court.  

Atty Constable informed the court that victims rights were not complied with for this hearing.
